# Workflow Rules

## Branch / Worktree Layout

Configured in `swarmforge/swarmforge.conf`:

| Role      | Backend | Worktree                | Branch                  |
|-----------|---------|-------------------------|-------------------------|
| architect | claude  | main working directory  | currently checked out (`main`) |
| coder     | codex   | `.worktrees/coder`      | `swarmforge-coder`      |
| reviewer  | codex   | `.worktrees/reviewer`   | `swarmforge-reviewer`   |
| logger    | none    | main working directory  | (tail-only utility)     |

At startup, every agent must:

1. Discover its assigned worktree and branch by checking `.swarmforge/sessions.tsv` and `git rev-parse --abbrev-ref HEAD`.
2. Remember that assignment for the rest of the session.
3. Refuse to work in any other branch or worktree. If the layout is missing or wrong, stop and report — do not silently repair.

## Handoff Chain

`architect` → `coder` → `reviewer` → (`coder` for follow-up | `architect` for merge into main).

Use `swarmtools/notify-agent.sh <role> "<message>"` for every handoff. Every notification must include:

- The branch name and the latest commit hash on that branch.
- A one-line summary of what changed.
- Which quality gates ran and their result (e.g. `lint: pass; busted behavior: pass; busted guards: pass`).
- Any open question or decision the next role must resolve.

## Merge Direction

- Coder merges from `swarmforge-architect` (or `main`, depending on what the architect committed) before starting work.
- Reviewer merges from `swarmforge-coder` before reviewing.
- Architect merges reviewer-accepted changes into `main` only after the reviewer's notification confirms all gates passed.

Merge accepted changes only from the role that produced them. Do not pull arbitrary branches.

## Discipline

- One scenario or one small slice per coder iteration. Stop before scope grows.
- The reviewer may refactor for testability but must preserve behavior; reviewer changes return to the coder for acknowledgement, not silent acceptance.
- Do not commit unrelated local edits or generated artifacts.
- Do not skip hooks (`--no-verify`) or signing (`--no-gpg-sign`) without explicit human approval.
- The human user is the final authority and may override any rule in writing.
